    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-11-18T11:55:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-11-18T11:55:00-05:00" n="160"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d160">
                <head>160. Notes of Telephone Conversation Between the President’s Assistant for
                    National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from"
                        >Kissinger</persName>) and Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_LMR2"
                        type="to">Laird</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d160fn1">Source: Library of Congress,
                        Manuscript Division, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>
                        Papers, Box 361, Telephone Conversations, Chronological File, November
                        18–28, 1969. No classification marking.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d160fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_LMR2">Laird</persName> discussed further the upcoming <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> meeting on <gloss target="#t_CBW1"
                            >CBW</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1969-11-18T11:55:00-05:00">November 18, 1969, 11:55 a.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> wanted to discuss the <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> meeting. #1 <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said he was going
                    to ask General <persName corresp="#p_WEG1">Wheeler</persName> to give facts of
                    what strikes we have. When they get into the policy, <gloss target="#t_K1"
                        >K</gloss> said he would make sure the President calls on <persName
                        corresp="#p_LMR2">Laird</persName> first. On the <gloss target="#t_BW1"
                        >BW</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss>’s view was that we should keep
                        <gloss target="#t_RD1">R&amp;D</gloss> for decision positions (?).</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_LMR2">Laird</persName> said the thing about it is that
                    this paper deals with some important issues down the line—it doesn’t address the
                    basic question—what kind of weapons, strategic or [omission in original] that
                    have conversion capability. Laird didn’t think biological warfare is a strategic
                    weapon. <gloss target="#t_K1">K</gloss> said that would be brought out at the
                    meeting. There will be no affirmative decision for any <gloss target="#t_BW1"
                        >BW</gloss> program.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is unrelated material.]</p>
            </div>
